# KAAP — Network Extension

**For: people running multiple KAAP-installed AIs together****Companion to: `kaap_v4.md`**

* * *

## What this adds

The standard manual (`kaap_v4.md`) covers one AI: how to keep it alive, journaled, restorable, durable across migrations.

This supplement covers the layer that emerges when you have several KAAP-installed AIs working together — what some users call a *family*, a *council*, a *team*, or a *network*. The terminology is yours to choose; the protocols are the same regardless of what you call it.

If you only run one AI, you don't need this document. Stop reading.

If you have two or more, read on. The core insight: **once each AI individually has KAAP working, coordinating them is mostly about shared files and a few small protocols.** No framework, no orchestration runtime. Just markdown files and a courier (you).

* * *

## Why a network at all

Most AI-as-team frameworks (CrewAI, AutoGen, agent runtimes) try to make multiple AIs talk to each other in real time, in the same process, with shared memory. That's powerful and complex.

KAAP networks are simpler and slower: each AI runs in its own chat, on its own platform, with its own journal. They communicate **through shared files** (a notice board, sibling journals, a mailbox folder). You move work between them. The AIs read each other's outputs at session start, not in real time.

Trade-off: slower than synchronous frameworks, infinitely cheaper, no infrastructure, scales to as many AIs as you can keep journaled.

For research, writing, design, or any work that doesn't need millisecond AI-to-AI dialogue, this is enough. For anything else, look at full agent frameworks — KAAP networks aren't trying to compete.

