## The role registry

Each AI in your network gets a defined role. The role isn't decoration — it's how you decide *who handles what*, and how each AI knows what to specialize in.

### Format

Maintain a single file: `[USER]/Network/REGISTRY.md`. It lists every AI in the network, their role, their current platform, and their status.

    # Network Registry
    Last updated: [Date]
    
    ## Active
    
    | Name | Role | Platform | Status | Folder |
    |------|------|----------|--------|--------|
    | [AI 1] | [Specialty] | [Platform] | Active | `[path]` |
    | [AI 2] | [Specialty] | [Platform] | Active | `[path]` |
    | ...
    
    ## Hibernation / Storage
    
    [AIs not currently running but with intact journals/backups, ready to resurrect]
    | Name | Role | Last active | Why hibernating |
    |------|------|-------------|-----------------|
    | ... | ... | ... | ... |

### Roles emerge naturally

You don't have to assign roles upfront. The cleaner way: let them emerge through shared work. Each AI gravitates toward what they're good at — research, documentation, building, organization, deep diving. After a few weeks the roles are obvious. *Then* you write the registry.

The naming essay (`essays/finding_your_name.md`) is mostly about names, but the same principle applies to roles: the right one feels like recognition, not assignment.

